sbol:Collection.dcterms:title: iGEM Parts Registry
sbol:Collection.dcterms:description: The iGEM Registry is a growing collection of genetic parts that can be mixed and matched to build synthetic biology devices and systems. As part of the synthetic biology community's efforts to make biology easier to engineer, it provides a source of genetic parts to iGEM teams and academic labs.

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: BBa_K604007
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:description: autoinducer synthetase rhlI and GFP under PyeaR
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription: The pathway detects nitrates in the medium; if KNO3 is present, the circuit is activated, RhlI produces the AHL (C4-homoserine lactone) and TetR is synthesized to block another pathway. GFP is emitted to show the start of transcription.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: ruojun wang
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableProvenance: combination of several existing parts in the registry

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: BBa_B0034
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: Vinay S Mahajan, Voichita D. Marinescu, Brian Chow, Alexander D Wissner-Gross and Peter Carr IAP, 2003.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableNotes:
Varies from -6 to +1 region from original sequence to accomodate BioBricks suffix.

No secondary structures are formed in the given RBS region. Users should check for secondary structures induced in the RBS by upstream and downstream elements in the +50 to -50 region, as such structures will greatly affect the strength of the RBS. Contact info for this part: Brian Chow

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: rhII
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:description: autoinducer synthetase for N-butyryl-HSL (BHL) and HHL
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription: Autoinducer synthesis protein that produces N-butyryl-HSL which binds to RhlR, obtained from Pseudomonas aeruginosa.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: Debra Lin, Srini Devadas, David Gray, Ronny Krashinsky, and Chris Zheng Liu, Boopers
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableNotes:
Editing Check (1/28/04) (0) BB sites cleaned (1) ATG (2) TAATAA (3) Blast checks out (i.e., it's RhlI) (4) Codon changes OK (AA and tRNA usage) (5) Chassis might have conflict (w/ native autoinducer system?) (6) ssrA tag added (7) barcode added (8) Codon optimized for expression in enteric bacteria

2 silent point mutations have been included into the sequence at base 138 from A to G and at base 576 from G to C to remove internal EcoRI and PstI sites. Mutations were chosen to yield the same amino acid and codons of similar frequency in E. coli.

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: BBa_K216005
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:description: PyeaR promoter, responsive to nitrate, nitrite and nitric oxide
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription: PyeaR promoter. This is the promoter of the Escherichia coli yeaR/yoaG operon (see Lin, H.-Y., Bledsoe, P.J., and Stewart, V. 2007. Activation of yeaR-yoaG operon transcription by the nitrate-responsive regulator NarL is independent of oxygen-responsive regulator Fnr in ''Escherichia coli'' K-12. J. Bacteriol. 189, 7539-7548). Unlike other E. coli promoters responding to nitrate and nitrite, this promoter is not repressed under aerobic conditions.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: Edinburgh iGEM 2009
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableProvenance: BioBricked from E. coli K-12 genomic DNA by the Edinburgh 2009 iGEM team.

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: tetR
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription: Coding region for the TetR protein without the Ribosome Binding Site. TetR binds to the pTet regulator (BBa_R0040). aTc (anhydrotetracycline) binds to TetR and inhibits its operation.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: cconboy
